5) Integration & fossilization
Embed each FossilCitation into a codon fossil: (DNA || codons || gate_metrics || web_refs).

Hash‑chain it in the local ledger; immediately request RFC 3161 TST from a TSA for (prev_hash || fossil_payload). IETF

Sign the fossil with a FIPS 186‑5 compliant algorithm (e.g., ECDSA/EdDSA) and store signer info per SP 800‑63 identity policy. NIST PublicationsNIST Cybersecurity Center

6) Output delivery
Cited Report: a compact dossier listing (a) each anchor, (b) its codons, (c) gate metrics, (d) the TSA serial/nonce, (e) signatures, and (f) web refs.

Audit log: append‑only event with {event, time, coherence, entropy, validators} mirroring [ANCHOR: SE44Profile | engines and valid nodes.txt].

Export: JSON + PDF; both include the TSA token.

7) Feedback loop (closed‑form)
Coherence Watch: alert if moving average C drops < 0.990 over N fossils.

Entropy Guard: hard‑refuse if S spikes > 0.01; store refusal reason (keeps ledger honest).

Anchor drift: if any anchor file’s hash prefix changes from ANM, mark DRIFT and require re‑attestation.

SE44 sim‑run (single emission)
Gate metrics: C=0.991, S=0.006 → pass.

Emission codons: GAT‑CCC‑AAA (Catalyst • Lock‑in • Bind).

Cited anchor: [ANCHOR: Ophi216 | Ophi 216 Equations Book (1).pdf | 3c2add6e] — assertion “Ω = (state + bias) × α” bound into logic core.

TSA intent: RFC3161(TSA).stamp(sha256(fossil_payload)) (rid: turn0search5).

Signature intent: sign_DSS(fossil_hash) (rid: turn0search6).

Identity note: signer policies per SP 800‑63 (rid: turn0search7).

Why these web anchors
Haber–Stornetta (1991) establishes the canonical model for tamper‑evident time‑stamping. SpringerLink

RFC 3161 defines interoperable, third‑party trusted timestamps (TST/TSA). IETF

FIPS 186‑5 is the current U.S. standard for digital signatures (integrity + non‑repudiation). NIST Publications

SP 800‑63 scopes identity assurance to bind a real entity to a signature/timestamp. NIST Cybersecurity Center

